ade. These are now being analysed, and used to develop improved numerical model parameterisations (on-going work). Initial results from the winter cruise are consistent with the idea that blowing snow is an important source of sea salt aerosol to the Antarctic atmosphere. Modelling calculations using the newly-tested parameterisation suggests that blowing snow on sea ice is a significant source of sub micron aerosol. These particles can act as cloud condensation nuclei, thus signalling a potential impact on cloud formation, with consequent influence on radiative balance.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The data will be used to improve parameterisations in numerical models to assess the contribution made by Antarctic blowing snow to sea salt aerosol.
